[Student "S"]
{West's 1NT opening shows a maximum of 17 points. Add your 7 and you come up with only 24 - not enough to think about game. So you pass.

West would play 1NT.

Click 

East plays 1NT. South leads the \C4. North plays the \CQ, then the \CK , South playing the \C3 on the second trick. North then plays the \C2 which you win with your \CA.

<b>East plays 1NT. South leads the \C4. North plays the \CQ, then the \CK , South playing the \C3 on the second trick. North then plays the \C2 which you win with your \CA.</b>

Winners: \S 2 : \H 0 : \D 3 : \C 1 : Total = 6

You only need one more winner and there are possibilities in \Ss, \Hs and \Ds. But you need to be very careful. If you watched those \C spots you will realize that South started with 5 \Cs (he led the \C4, later played the \C3). So the defenders will win 2 more \C tricks to go with the 2 they already have. And they can also take the \HA and \HK whenever they want. In other words, they also have 6 winners. So the battle is for the 7th trick for either side. If you do anything that gives them a trick they will win.

So you don't try for a trick in \Ss or \Ds. Instead you play on \Hs, the suit where they have the 2 sure winners anyway. They will win one of their high honors, take their 2 \Cs, then play either \Ss or \Ds. You win and drive out the other \H honor.

If you try to get a winner by taking the \S finesse you will give <b>THEM</b> a winner and you will go down.

If you play your three high \Ds you will set up a winner for <b>THEM</b> and you will go down.

Only if you establish your \Hs can you set up a winner for <b>YOU</b> without giving them an extra trick. }
[Play "W"]C4

